WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.00 --> 00:00:02.76
As we continue to observe Black History Month,

00:00:02.76 --> 00:00:06.03
it's hard to believe there are still people alive today who

00:00:06.03 --> 00:00:08.28
had a parent born into slavery.

00:00:08.28 --> 00:00:10.59
Daniel Smith, who's almost 90 years old,

00:00:10.59 --> 00:00:12.06
is one of the few left.

00:00:12.06 --> 00:00:15.06
Jan Crawford spoke with him about his incredible story,

00:00:15.06 --> 00:00:18.51
which reflects the arc of race relations in America,

00:00:18.51 --> 00:00:22.20
from slavery to civil rights activism and the fight

00:00:22.20 --> 00:00:24.60
to end systemic discrimination.

00:00:24.60 --> 00:00:26.70
Jan is outside the National Museum

00:00:26.70 --> 00:00:30.03
of African-American History and Culture in Washington.

00:00:30.03 --> 00:00:31.47
A great story today, Jan.

00:00:31.47 --> 00:00:32.01
Good morning.

00:00:32.01 --> 00:00:34.69


00:00:34.69 --> 00:00:35.65
Good morning, Michelle.

00:00:35.65 --> 00:00:37.69
It's an inspiring, incredible story.

00:00:37.69 --> 00:00:39.97
And what's even more incredible, the messages

00:00:39.97 --> 00:00:43.03
that Daniel Smith heard from his father, a freed slave,

00:00:43.03 --> 00:00:46.96
survivor, the strongest of the strong, so similar to what

00:00:46.96 --> 00:00:48.88
many other children of freed slaves

00:00:48.88 --> 00:00:50.47
heard from their parents.

00:00:50.47 --> 00:00:53.99
It's a story history has forgotten.

00:00:53.99 --> 00:00:55.84
We are survivors.

00:00:55.84 --> 00:00:58.66
Daniel Smith is one of the last living links

00:00:58.66 --> 00:01:01.00
to America's original sin.

00:01:01.00 --> 00:01:02.93
Your grandparents were enslaved.

00:01:02.93 --> 00:01:03.43
Correct.

00:01:03.43 --> 00:01:06.40
Your father was born the property of a white man.

00:01:06.40 --> 00:01:07.03
Yep.

00:01:07.03 --> 00:01:10.30
His father, Abram was born into bondage in Virginia

00:01:10.30 --> 00:01:11.98
in the early 1860s.

00:01:11.98 --> 00:01:15.49
He was 70 when his youngest son, Daniel, was born.

00:01:15.49 --> 00:01:17.74
He used to tell these stories--

00:01:17.74 --> 00:01:20.95
--stories about the inhumanity their ancestors

00:01:20.95 --> 00:01:23.53
suffered and survived.

00:01:23.53 --> 00:01:28.33
Father said you could hear them screaming and crying

00:01:28.33 --> 00:01:30.07
at the whipping poles.

00:01:30.07 --> 00:01:33.40
But the interesting thing, my father

00:01:33.40 --> 00:01:39.46
never allowed you to talk negatively about America.

00:01:39.46 --> 00:01:41.83
His father believed, like other freed

00:01:41.83 --> 00:01:46.27
slaves in this new America, his young son would be great.

00:01:46.27 --> 00:01:49.60
He grabbed me and shook me.

00:01:49.60 --> 00:01:53.29
He said you have nothing to cry about.

00:01:53.29 --> 00:01:54.71
This is America.

00:01:54.71 --> 00:01:57.61
We came from the strongest of the strong.

00:01:57.61 --> 00:02:00.28
We survived the ships.

00:02:00.28 --> 00:02:00.85
The ship?

00:02:00.85 --> 00:02:05.21
He gave me a signal to be strong and to survive.

00:02:05.21 --> 00:02:09.88
And not just survive, but thrive and fight for true freedom.

00:02:09.88 --> 00:02:11.24
John Lewis.

00:02:11.24 --> 00:02:13.30
You have a lot of memories with him.

00:02:13.30 --> 00:02:13.87
Right.

00:02:13.87 --> 00:02:15.82
Smith's living room is a testament

00:02:15.82 --> 00:02:18.61
to his generation's struggle for equality.

00:02:18.61 --> 00:02:20.26
[VOCALIZING]

00:02:20.26 --> 00:02:24.16
He was there for Martin Luther King Jr.'s March on Washington.

00:02:24.16 --> 00:02:26.41
I want to remember his someday--

00:02:26.41 --> 00:02:28.60
--little Black boys and Black girls--

00:02:28.60 --> 00:02:30.00
--can walk hand in hand--

00:02:30.00 --> 00:02:32.53
--with little white boys and white girls

00:02:32.53 --> 00:02:33.95
as sisters and brothers.

00:02:33.95 --> 00:02:35.87
I have a dream today.

00:02:35.87 --> 00:02:38.56
Well, I was saying yes and yes.

00:02:38.56 --> 00:02:40.41
(CHANTING) We are not--

00:02:40.41 --> 00:02:42.73
Smith followed that dream to Alabama,

00:02:42.73 --> 00:02:45.72
where he helped lead the fight for voting rights.

00:02:45.72 --> 00:02:48.15
He witnessed firsthand the terror.

00:02:48.15 --> 00:02:51.45
Smith remembers the Ku Klux Klan torching his office.

00:02:51.45 --> 00:02:54.54
And one night while driving, a car full of white men

00:02:54.54 --> 00:02:57.00
chased him down a dark road.

00:02:57.00 --> 00:02:58.80
Then all of a sudden, boom.

00:02:58.80 --> 00:02:59.61
They hit me.

00:02:59.61 --> 00:03:03.51
And so I sped up as fast as my car would go.

00:03:03.51 --> 00:03:08.04
And then they come alongside me, ""[BLEEP] pull over,

00:03:08.04 --> 00:03:10.18
you Black [BLEEP]."

00:03:10.18 --> 00:03:12.85
And I said, "No, this Black [BLEEP]

00:03:12.85 --> 00:03:17.86
not pulling over," because if they catch you, you're gone.

00:03:17.86 --> 00:03:20.11
That must have been the most terrifying.

00:03:20.11 --> 00:03:21.94
I wasn't as scared.

00:03:21.94 --> 00:03:23.41
I was angry.

00:03:23.41 --> 00:03:26.29
But it stays with you up to 89.

00:03:26.29 --> 00:03:28.95
Like you can still feel that feeling.

00:03:28.95 --> 00:03:30.10
Oh yes, yeah, right.

00:03:30.10 --> 00:03:33.01
Smith went on to a successful career in government--

00:03:33.01 --> 00:03:34.84
[VOCALIZING]

00:03:34.84 --> 00:03:37.84
--and served as head usher at the National Cathedral,

00:03:37.84 --> 00:03:40.18
where he led presidents to prayer.

00:03:40.18 --> 00:03:45.76
An incredible life, inspired by a generation history forgets.

00:03:45.76 --> 00:03:48.22
We want to think that happened so long ago.

00:03:48.22 --> 00:03:51.28
Author Sana Butler says the children of freed slaves,

00:03:51.28 --> 00:03:54.95
like Smith, heard similar messages from their parents.

00:03:54.95 --> 00:03:57.43
Mothers and fathers said we didn't

00:03:57.43 --> 00:04:01.66
survive for you to be anything other than great.

00:04:01.66 --> 00:04:03.79
In her book, Sugar of the crop, Butler

00:04:03.79 --> 00:04:06.79
spoke to more than a dozen children of slaves, all of whom

00:04:06.79 --> 00:04:07.93
now are gone.

00:04:07.93 --> 00:04:10.84
Instead of anger, they were taught, like Smith,

00:04:10.84 --> 00:04:12.79
they could do anything.

00:04:12.79 --> 00:04:17.22
After the Civil War, Blacks truly

00:04:17.22 --> 00:04:18.60
believed the worst is over.

00:04:18.60 --> 00:04:19.53
The worst was over.

00:04:19.53 --> 00:04:20.73
The worst was over.

00:04:20.73 --> 00:04:23.52
So they had this immigrant mentality,

00:04:23.52 --> 00:04:29.04
that we are going to go out and achieve everything that we can.

00:04:29.04 --> 00:04:31.08
They didn't anticipate the barriers white

00:04:31.08 --> 00:04:33.06
America would erect.

00:04:33.06 --> 00:04:35.94
But their message, like the one from Smith's father,

00:04:35.94 --> 00:04:39.03
was you are the strongest of the strong.

00:04:39.03 --> 00:04:43.33
People always say it can't be done.

00:04:43.33 --> 00:04:44.47
You can't do this.

00:04:44.47 --> 00:04:45.40
You can't do that.

00:04:45.40 --> 00:04:46.77
I don't believe that.

00:04:46.77 --> 00:04:49.47
If you tell me that, I'm going to do it.

00:04:49.47 --> 00:04:51.54
You hear people say today, but America

00:04:51.54 --> 00:04:53.07
has made so much progress.

00:04:53.07 --> 00:04:53.76
It has.

00:04:53.76 --> 00:04:54.88
But--

00:04:54.88 --> 00:04:56.97
No, it really has.

00:04:56.97 --> 00:05:01.06
When I voted for Obama, I mean, I was shaking.

00:05:01.06 --> 00:05:03.00
I couldn't believe I was doing this.

00:05:03.00 --> 00:05:06.45
A Black man-- we've made a lot of progress.

00:05:06.45 --> 00:05:09.13
But he says not nearly enough.

00:05:09.13 --> 00:05:14.64
We cannot continue as a nation with people hating each other.

00:05:14.64 --> 00:05:17.58
My father, he never hated anyone.

00:05:17.58 --> 00:05:18.87
You never saw that from him?

00:05:18.87 --> 00:05:20.52
Right, no, never saw it.

00:05:20.52 --> 00:05:23.37
What would your message be for the future?

00:05:23.37 --> 00:05:24.03
Be kind.

00:05:24.03 --> 00:05:26.13
We need more kindness.

00:05:26.13 --> 00:05:29.43
I look back in terms of my crazy life.

00:05:29.43 --> 00:05:34.59
And I think it all came from my father saying do good things.

00:05:34.59 --> 00:05:37.21
Do good things.

00:05:37.21 --> 00:05:39.88
Now, Daniel Smith turns 90 next month.

00:05:39.88 --> 00:05:42.19
He's planning to share his story in a book

00:05:42.19 --> 00:05:45.37
that he's writing with his wife, Loretta, called Son of a Slave.

00:05:45.37 --> 00:05:48.94
It's a reminder that that dark chapter in America's history

00:05:48.94 --> 00:05:51.25
is not that far in the past.

00:05:51.25 --> 00:05:52.39
Tony?

00:05:52.39 --> 00:05:54.11
Hey, Jan, I was just thinking that people

00:05:54.11 --> 00:05:55.15
say it's ancient history.

00:05:55.15 --> 00:05:56.53
But it can't be that ancient when

00:05:56.53 --> 00:06:00.58
you have the son of a person who was born into bondage.

00:06:00.58 --> 00:06:03.74
That person thought the future was brighter for his son.

00:06:03.74 --> 00:06:05.53
And it turns out that was true, but there's

00:06:05.53 --> 00:06:06.58
a lot of work left to do.

00:06:06.58 --> 00:06:08.80
Jan, thank you very much for a very skillful piece.

00:06:08.80 --> 00:06:10.72
Yeah, skillful, and so reminds me

00:06:10.72 --> 00:06:12.76
of my father, my grandmother.

00:06:12.76 --> 00:06:17.27
But the point that he made, anger is important.

00:06:17.27 --> 00:06:19.81
It's what you do with the anger and how

00:06:19.81 --> 00:06:22.75
you make change with the anger.

00:06:22.75 --> 00:06:23.90
People get angry.

00:06:23.90 --> 00:06:25.24
He said he was angry.

00:06:25.24 --> 00:06:28.03
But it's like making that constructive.

00:06:28.03 --> 00:06:28.57
Of course.

00:06:28.57 --> 00:06:30.22
And he did it throughout his life.

00:06:30.22 --> 00:06:30.97
No doubt about it.

00:06:30.97 --> 00:06:33.91
And not every Black person is a descendant of someone

00:06:33.91 --> 00:06:34.72
who was enslaved.

00:06:34.72 --> 00:06:39.34
But if you are, you are strong, because those before you

00:06:39.34 --> 00:06:41.38
were the strongest of the strongest.

00:06:41.38 --> 00:06:43.12
A lesson for a lot of people.

00:06:43.12 --> 00:06:45.94
It's like move beyond--

00:06:45.94 --> 00:06:46.54
Move forward.

00:06:46.54 --> 00:06:47.57
--and move forward.

00:06:47.57 --> 00:06:48.87
Yeah.

00:06:48.87 --> 00:06:49.37
